"It's on the strength of observation and reflection that one finds a way.  So we must dig and delve unceasingingly," stated Claude Monet.  
Collecting my notebook and pencils, I headed to the backyard to sit under the peach tree to sketch.  
For an hour each day, after school, when no one was home, I reveled in the shade and the coolness of the grass under my feet and savored the freedom.
My identity, at the time, remained more conventional.
I was expected to become a successful doctor, a dutiful Asian bride, have an obscene number of children, and live with my family.
My life rested on money, prestige, and status circling around racial authenticity.
Did I dare challenge and live outside this expectation?
